meta.name: I Hate School
meta.description:
I started working on this piece right after I woke up to my wife saying it was my turn to get up with the kids. 


I rolled out of bed with 2 whole hours of sleep and sat on the couch next to my oldest. He said, hey dad, you’re the one with the hundred dollar bill, will you give it to me so I can buy a go pro.


This got me thinking, when I was a kid, when did I realize the value of items?My earliest memory of value was a Magic the Gathering card The Black Lotus. My older sister was into it [magic] and she had traded a lotus away and then found out how much it was worth. Times were different as a kid though, we didn’t have google to answer all of our questions. We couldn’t just check to see which card was the rarest. 


	After a few sips of caffeine, I picked up the iPad to check twitter, but Procreate was still open from last night. If you don’t know me or follow me on twitter (@ih0dl) then you should know, I have terrible ADHD. It’s probably the worst. 


	So, while still thinking about the lotus I forgot the whole reason I picked up my iPad (twitter) and I started to sketch the flower from my childhood memory of the card. 


	When starting I expected to half ass doodle of a flower. I thought I would doodle and drink caffeine until I was ready to finish the WIP from the day prior.
Little did I know, I would end up spending 16 hours straight working on this flower. 


While working on it I started to think about value, and my sons question. When he asked me I said, “If you clean your room I will give you 10 bucks.” 


He replied,  “but, you already have the 100 you could just give me.”


I tried to explain value to him the best I could. He got bored and started singing a song and playing with a race car. 


I drifted back into my piece thinking about childhood and how fucked up shit was. My parents loved me to death, but we were definitely lower class trash. I say trash because I have grown to embrace it. I literally came from nothing and worked every minute to escape. While my understanding of value may have started with the playing card, it quickly expanded to how much I valued my escape. 


With this piece I wanted to summarize my life. It may have started as a doodle, but it turned into a story. Which I break down into 8 pieces.




“Dirty Water” - symbolizes my beginning, which I covered above so I won’t get detailed here.

“Broken Mirrors” - symbolizes the realization that the life I was living wasn’t normal. I could change the reflection I see staring back at me. 

“The 80s” - symbolizes my childhood which is filled with nostalgia that floods the brain with dopamine when I think about the technology back then (and into the 90s). 

“Radar” - symbolizes running, I thought I was escaping it all by joining the army. I thought that I was going to get away. You can run, but you cannot hide, no matter how good of camouflage you have. 

“The Bigger Picture” - symbolizes me reevaluating after battling PTSD from my time overseas. I lived in dark solitude for upwards of 5 years. Until I was ready to look at that broken mirror again.

“Black Lotus” - symbolizes me discovering my own value. This is when I decided I wasn’t just going to work to get by any more. This is when I was determined to break free. This is when I knew I was going to do something with this fucked up life. 

“I hate school” - symbolizes graduating college after dropping out of high school to work more and save money to escape. What a strange twist, I never thought I would do it. I almost opted out of the GI bill because they took 100 dollars per pay for a year to cover it.  

“Happy Accidents” - symbolizes me discovering NFTS. Before NFTs I was working in a hospital lab, and got fired during the peak of covid. I tried going up against a crooked ass drunk manager and she fired me the day I came back from bereavement leave. I had to bury my sister and then fight covid (pandemic not virus) with no income the next day.  While this may not seem too happy, the end of the story gets better. I discovered NFTs accidentally and I finally escaped.

meta.name: Ascending the Crystal Stairway #213/400
meta.description:
The artwork is a captivating visual poem that brings to life the reverence and aspirations found in 'The Way of the Bodhisattva (Bodhicharyavatara)' by Shantideva. It portrays a transcendental realm that mirrors the spiritual purity and devotion expressed in the verses. At the forefront sits a serene figure in meditation, clad in vibrant saffron robes, representing the practitioner's offering of themselves to the path of the Bodhisattva. This figure is a symbol of unwavering commitment to enlightenment and service to all beings, echoing the promise to be a devoted follower of the enlightened ones.

In the ethereal background, we observe a celestial Buddha seated within a crystalline structure that soars towards the heavens, resplendent with radiant light and embellished with precious gems. The environment conjures a sense of a fragrant bathing chamber, where the Buddhas and their heirs are honored and cleansed with the purest of waters, symbolic of the practitioner's cleansing from past misdeeds and the resolve to maintain purity henceforth.

The surrounding landscape is alive with organic and psychedelic patterns, resembling a fantastic and otherworldly ecosystem, thriving under a sky dotted with celestial bodies. This vivid scenery suggests the flourishing of wisdom and compassion under the guidance of the Bodhisattvas. The delicate fusion of colors and forms captures the vibrancy and dynamism of a universe transformed by the Bodhisattva's way, resonating with melody and song as described in the sacred text.

The artwork, as a whole, is a dynamic interplay between the grounded presence of the meditator and the sublime realm of the Buddhas, encapsulating the journey of transformation from samsara to nirvana, and the altruistic pledge to emancipate all beings from the cycles of suffering. It stands as a tribute to the spiritual journey and the Bodhisattva's path of compassionate action and boundless devotion.

meta.name: The Watcher
meta.description:
In a fascinating exploration of digital art interpretation, an AI language model has been employed to analyze a captivating collection of abstract pieces, delving into their visual elements, symbolism, and underlying themes. The AI's insightful analysis offers a fresh perspective on these mesmerizing artworks. As we delve into the details of each creation, let us embark on a journey through the realms of abstraction and fantasy, unraveling the enigmatic narratives and hidden meanings that lie within this captivating collection.

"The Watcher" is a captivating digital artwork that explores the themes of introspection and perception, employing a stylized and abstract representation of a man's face. Rendered in pink, purple, and yellow hues, the subject's gaze is directed to his left, as if he is observing something outside the frame or peering into an unseen world.

The background is intentionally left blurry and indistinct, which could possibly be interpreted as a female body silhouette, adding an air of mystery and further engaging the viewer's imagination. The man's eyes are enlarged and jagged, drawing attention to his unique perspective and vision. His irises are strikingly large, with rectangular pupils that feature jagged edges on their left sides, suggesting an unconventional and potentially distorted view of reality.

The absence of eyebrows on the man's face prevents the viewer from easily discerning his emotions, adding to the enigmatic quality of the piece. His eye-whites, visible in a yellowish-green hue with a single large vein in each eye, evoke a sense of intensity and focus. The artist has deliberately left the subject's hair undefined, with the top of his head appearing hilly, further emphasizing the abstract nature of the artwork.

The man's nose, seemingly facing left and possibly missing one nostril, invites the viewer to question their own perception and interpretation of the artwork. This ambiguity could be an intentional illusion created by the artist or simply a dark spot that adds to the complexity of the piece.

In "The Watcher," the artist masterfully employs abstraction and ambiguity to encourage viewers to reflect on their own perspectives and challenge their perceptions of reality. The artwork serves as a reminder that there is always more to see, understand, and interpret than what may be immediately apparent.

meta.name: The Enigmatic Entanglement
meta.description:
In a fascinating exploration of digital art interpretation, an AI language model has been employed to analyze a captivating collection of abstract pieces, delving into their visual elements, symbolism, and underlying themes. The AI's insightful analysis offers a fresh perspective on these mesmerizing artworks. The Analysis:  
"The Enigmatic Entanglement" is a bold and vibrant digital artwork that delves into the complexities of interconnectedness and relationships among various life forms. The composition is saturated with bright pinks and greens, evoking a sense of liveliness and energy that permeates the piece.

The central figures in the artwork - a man, bird, serpent, masked face, eyeless whale, and floppy pink fish - are entwined and piled atop one another, signifying the interdependence and interconnectedness of these disparate beings. Their gazes are collectively directed towards a neon green and magenta portal from which a six-legged starfish emerges, further emphasizing the theme of interconnectedness and shared curiosity.

The man, rendered in hues of pink, peach, and yellowish-green, points at the starfish while his wide-open mouth reveals an open doorway with dark steps leading upwards to a green door. This intriguing detail invites the viewer to consider the unknown and the potential for growth and transformation within each individual.

The bird, adorned with a gold chain and a key engraved with the word "private," holds the secrets and hidden aspects of life, suggesting that even in our interconnected world, there are still personal and private elements that remain locked away.

The ground, comprised of digital circles, offers a retro, 80s or 90s-era tech vibe, alluding to the influence of technology on the interconnectedness of life and the human experience. The serpent, with a blue bird in one nostril and a purple flower with a bee in the other, embodies the duality and balance of life.

In "The Enigmatic Entanglement," the artist challenges the viewer to contemplate the intricate web of connections and relationships that bind us to one another and to the world around us. The piece invites introspection and reflection on the various influences that shape our lives and the hidden aspects that are yet to be revealed.

The analysis:  
In this captivating digital artwork, the artist masterfully melds the realms of abstraction and fantasy, enveloping the viewer in a realm of unspoken narratives and enigmatic symbolism. The scene captures a wizard and a serpentine dragon, engaged in a cryptic exchange, each rendered in a striking posterized style, their hand-drawn lines and harmonious palette of pearl, green, peach, and yellow hues suggesting an otherworldly aura. The wizard's profile, with its gravity-defying eye and somber visage, is depicted in a manner reminiscent of Cubism, while his attire is adorned with a mesmerizing cacophony of abstract patterns in vibrant blues, pinks, and purples. As he conjures a fireball, its ethereal blue outline hints at a sublime and potent energy.

The inclusion of an enigmatic orange flower, inscrutably marked with a number three, elicits a sense of deeper meaning and perhaps even a connection to the three hearts in the upper left corner, possibly alluding to video game culture. The pixelated ground and comic book aesthetic further intertwine the digital and physical realms, challenging the viewer to discern where one ends and the other begins. The celestial backdrop, awash in dark blue and purple hues punctuated by digital circle outlines, mirrors the chromatic intensity of the fireball and sky, creating an immersive atmosphere.

One could argue that the piece grapples with the intricate relationship between technology and human imagination, as well as the increasingly blurred boundaries between the virtual and the tangible. The wizard's ambiguous gaze, which could be directed at either the dragon or the viewer, invites us to engage with this enigmatic narrative and contemplate the hidden messages that may reside within. Ultimately, the artwork serves as a powerful testament to the transformative and illusive nature of the digital age.

The sailboat in the water, the cave in the mountain, and the moon, which has turned blue, are all borrowed from other pieces within the collection, highlighting the interconnectedness of the various artworks.

The melting rabbit, holding one of the flowers from the daytime scene, serves as a poignant reminder of the fragility and impermanence of life. This piece invites the viewer to contemplate the multifaceted nature of reality and the transformative power of time.

meta.description:
This 1/1 mint is redeemable for the physical painting: 16x20 acrylic on canvas. After purchase, hit me up on [twitter](https://twitter.com/ih0dl) to set up shipping. 

The prohibition is the father of the bootlegger, the mother of the speakeasy. The war on art will be no different. We will continue to seek what you tell us we cannot have. We will never stop.  This painting was completed over the course of a year. I use a glass table to paint. After every session, I would scrape the dry paint off of the table and put it into a box. After a few months it was time to mix these shavings into the painting to create the trashiest texture ever seen on canvas. I tried trashart in 2020 and I fell in love with the culture. LONG LIVE TRASHART!

Collector has 90 days from the sale date to redeem physical painting. If the painting has not been redeemed within this timeframe,  the collector forfeits rights to the physical work. This NFT will remain 1/1 and no copies will be made.

meta.name: Not Another Whale
meta.description:
A 1 of 1 original crypto-artwork by iH0DL, 2020.

A study in texture and luminance inspired by the effortless ability of the octopus to change the color and texture of its skin. 

Since the first time I learned of the concept of evolution as a child I have been fascinated at the ability of life to adapt. The octopus is such a great example of evolution that chose intelligence over physicality. Since it is basically a snail, who lost its shell, it had to protect itself with its brains.  

While whales spent thousands of years developing one brain, the octopus built a different type of computer. It still features the main processor (brain) but also has a processor for each limb. An octa-core centralized processor ain’t got shit on the octopuses DΞCΞNTRALIZΞD ennead processor system. 

In crypto we refer to the deep pocketed hodlers as whales. While there is no denying the intelligence of the whale swimming in the sea of crypto, there are other fish cephalopods in the sea with an astute approach to DΞCΞNTRALIZATION. The approach of quantity can certainly be rewarding, especially when accumulating bitcoin. In a market where supply and demand rule, price can be manipulated easily by these cunning whales. 

This is why I included the bitcoin in the piece, Non Fungible Tokens may be the first store a value whose price cannot be manipulated.  NFTs in the form of art derive value in a magical, non monetary way. A unique piece of arts value cannot be manipulated when scarcity is exchanged for unparalleled fungibility. 

You can buy more than one bitcoin, but you cannot buy more than one “Not another Whale” NFT.

meta.description:
There are 22 cards without suits in a tarot deck known as  "Major Arcana" cards.

There will be 22 tokenized cards of each "Major Arcana", themed toward NFT / Cryptoart which will allow for 22 complete collections. 
These cards will include:
The Fool, The Magician, The High Priestess, The Empress, The Emperor, The Hierophant, The Lovers, The Chariot, Strength, The Hermit, Wheel of Fortune, Justice, The Hanged Man, Death, Temperance, The Devil, The Tower, The Star, The Moon, The Sun, Judgement, and The World.

This still leaves the option for the "Minor Arcana" which is similar to a deck of playing-cards you may be more familiar with. The Minor Arcana consists of 56 cards total, with four suits, 14 cards in each. Each suit has 10 numbered cards and four face cards or court cards.

meta.name: The Broken
meta.description:
In a fascinating exploration of digital art interpretation, an AI language model has been employed to analyze a captivating collection of abstract pieces, delving into their visual elements, symbolism, and underlying themes. The AI's insightful analysis offers a fresh perspective on these mesmerizing artworks. As we delve into the details of each creation, let us embark on a journey through the realms of abstraction and fantasy, unraveling the enigmatic narratives and hidden meanings that lie within this captivating collection.

The Analysis:  
This work delves into the depths of human emotion, vulnerability, and the complexities of love and loss. The man in the artwork, with his water-like skin in hues of green, blue, and purple, embodies the fluidity and ever-changing nature of human emotion. The snake on his shoulder, which seems both a part of him and separate, symbolizes the darker, more hidden aspects of the self that may emerge in times of emotional turmoil.

The wilting, multicolored flower held by the man represents the fragile and ephemeral nature of love, as well as the beauty that can still be found even in the most trying of times. The pond of water leaking down his back, housing a single fish, speaks to the delicate balance between emotional resilience and the overwhelming weight of loss.

The broken heart in front of the man, visible only to him, emphasizes the personal and internal nature of emotional struggles. The man holding an engagement ring in a red box behind his back highlights the unspoken, hidden intentions and desires that often accompany love and heartache. The heart-print boxers and pointed toe boots add a touch of humor and relatability, grounding the scene in the reality of everyday life.

The closed space surrounding the man contrasts with the open, blueish-white ground beyond, creating a sense of confinement and isolation that many individuals experience during difficult emotional periods. This piece invites the viewer to reflect on their own emotional journey and the delicate balance between love, loss, and personal growth.

meta.description:
The Error Collection by iH0DL was previously labeled, "iH0DL Decentralized Art." In December 2021, iH0DL started buying back tokens from this collection, which was his first collection on opensea. The legacy OS contracts allow for easy metadata editing (if you own the token.) So he started buying them back, and "corrupting" the original images, replacing them eternally with an ERROR. This error will remain attached to the token as long as it is not in possession of the artist. Once iH0DL buys back any piece in this collection, it's previous image will be corrupted, and lost forever!

All Tokens purchased as an "error" are formatted to fit the Meural Digital Art Frame by Netgear. These will also include a high resolution download (IPFS) to the original animation. Each 1:1 at 2048 x 2048 px.

meta.name: Happy Accidents
meta.description:
I started working on this piece right after I woke up to my wife saying it was my turn to get up with the kids. 


I rolled out of bed with 2 whole hours of sleep and sat on the couch next to my oldest. He said, hey dad, you’re the one with the hundred dollar bill, will you give it to me so I can buy a go pro.


This got me thinking, when I was a kid, when did I realize the value of items?My earliest memory of value was a Magic the Gathering card The Black Lotus. My older sister was into it [magic] and she had traded a lotus away and then found out how much it was worth. Times were different as a kid though, we didn’t have google to answer all of our questions. We couldn’t just check to see which card was the rarest. 


	After a few sips of caffeine, I picked up the iPad to check twitter, but Procreate was still open from last night. If you don’t know me or follow me on twitter (@ih0dl) then you should know, I have terrible ADHD. It’s probably the worst. 


	So, while still thinking about the lotus I forgot the whole reason I picked up my iPad (twitter) and I started to sketch the flower from my childhood memory of the card. 


	When starting I expected to half ass doodle of a flower. I thought I would doodle and drink caffeine until I was ready to finish the WIP from the day prior.
Little did I know, I would end up spending 16 hours straight working on this flower. 


While working on it I started to think about value, and my sons question. When he asked me I said, “If you clean your room I will give you 10 bucks.” 


He replied,  “but, you already have the 100 you could just give me.”


I tried to explain value to him the best I could. He got bored and started singing a song and playing with a race car. 


I drifted back into my piece thinking about childhood and how fucked up shit was. My parents loved me to death, but we were definitely lower class trash. I say trash because I have grown to embrace it. I literally came from nothing and worked every minute to escape. While my understanding of value may have started with the playing card, it quickly expanded to how much I valued my escape. 


With this piece I wanted to summarize my life. It may have started as a doodle, but it turned into a story. Which I break down into 8 pieces.




“Dirty Water” - symbolizes my beginning, which I covered above so I won’t get detailed here.

“Broken Mirrors” - symbolizes the realization that the life I was living wasn’t normal. I could change the reflection I see staring back at me. 

“The 80s” - symbolizes my childhood which is filled with nostalgia that floods the brain with dopamine when I think about the technology back then (and into the 90s). 

“Radar” - symbolizes running, I thought I was escaping it all by joining the army. I thought that I was going to get away. You can run, but you cannot hide, no matter how good of camouflage you have. 

“The Bigger Picture” - symbolizes me reevaluating after battling PTSD from my time overseas. I lived in dark solitude for upwards of 5 years. Until I was ready to look at that broken mirror again.

“Black Lotus” - symbolizes me discovering my own value. This is when I decided I wasn’t just going to work to get by any more. This is when I was determined to break free. This is when I knew I was going to do something with this fucked up life. 

“I hate school” - symbolizes graduating college after dropping out of high school to work more and save money to escape. What a strange twist, I never thought I would do it. I almost opted out of the GI bill because they took 100 dollars per pay for a year to cover it.  

“Happy Accidents” - symbolizes me discovering NFTS. Before NFTs I was working in a hospital lab, and got fired during the peak of covid. I tried going up against a crooked ass drunk manager and she fired me the day I came back from bereavement leave. I had to bury my sister and then fight covid (pandemic not virus) with no income the next day.  While this may not seem too happy, the end of the story gets better. I discovered NFTs accidentally and I finally escaped.

I rolled out of bed with 2 whole hours of sleep and sat on the couch next to my oldest. He said, hey dad, you’re the one with the hundred dollar bill, will you give it to me so I can buy a go pro.


This got me thinking, when I was a kid, when did I realize the value of items?My earliest memory of value was a Magic the Gathering card The Black Lotus. My older sister was into it [magic] and she had traded a lotus away and then found out how much it was worth. Times were different as a kid though, we didn’t have google to answer all of our questions. We couldn’t just check to see which card was the rarest. 


	After a few sips of caffeine, I picked up the iPad to check twitter, but Procreate was still open from last night. If you don’t know me or follow me on twitter (@ih0dl) then you should know, I have terrible ADHD. It’s probably the worst. 


	So, while still thinking about the lotus I forgot the whole reason I picked up my iPad (twitter) and I started to sketch the flower from my childhood memory of the card. 


	When starting I expected to half ass doodle of a flower. I thought I would doodle and drink caffeine until I was ready to finish the WIP from the day prior.
Little did I know, I would end up spending 16 hours straight working on this flower. 


While working on it I started to think about value, and my sons question. When he asked me I said, “If you clean your room I will give you 10 bucks.” 


He replied,  “but, you already have the 100 you could just give me.”


I tried to explain value to him the best I could. He got bored and started singing a song and playing with a race car. 


I drifted back into my piece thinking about childhood and how fucked up shit was. My parents loved me to death, but we were definitely lower class trash. I say trash because I have grown to embrace it. I literally came from nothing and worked every minute to escape. While my understanding of value may have started with the playing card, it quickly expanded to how much I valued my escape. 


With this piece I wanted to summarize my life. It may have started as a doodle, but it turned into a story. Which I break down into 8 pieces.




“Dirty Water” - symbolizes my beginning, which I covered above so I won’t get detailed here.

“Broken Mirrors” - symbolizes the realization that the life I was living wasn’t normal. I could change the reflection I see staring back at me. 

“The 80s” - symbolizes my childhood which is filled with nostalgia that floods the brain with dopamine when I think about the technology back then (and into the 90s). 

“Radar” - symbolizes running, I thought I was escaping it all by joining the army. I thought that I was going to get away. You can run, but you cannot hide, no matter how good of camouflage you have. 

“The Bigger Picture” - symbolizes me reevaluating after battling PTSD from my time overseas. I lived in dark solitude for upwards of 5 years. Until I was ready to look at that broken mirror again.

“Black Lotus” - symbolizes me discovering my own value. This is when I decided I wasn’t just going to work to get by any more. This is when I was determined to break free. This is when I knew I was going to do something with this fucked up life. 

“I hate school” - symbolizes graduating college after dropping out of high school to work more and save money to escape. What a strange twist, I never thought I would do it. I almost opted out of the GI bill because they took 100 dollars per pay for a year to cover it.  

“Happy Accidents” - symbolizes me discovering NFTS. Before NFTs I was working in a hospital lab, and got fired during the peak of covid. I tried going up against a crooked ass drunk manager and she fired me the day I came back from bereavement leave. I had to bury my sister and then fight covid (pandemic not virus) with no income the next day.  While this may not seem too happy, the end of the story gets better. I discovered NFTs accidentally and I finally escaped.

meta.name: Tab 9
meta.description: Welcome to my (8192 x 6144 px) browser history. A place where I go when I'm feeling down about the world, or myself, or anything. It's where I go for answers, help, or to hide; art is my gateway drug.  During the initial invasion of Ukraine by Russia, I was struggling with mental health, which lead to this series. It was my escape from reality through reality.  This series will be a total of 14 pieces. 13 1/1's in various dimensions ranging from 1024x2048 to 2048x2048. Each of the 13 1/1's will have up to 37 variations which will be controlled through the unlockable content using rarible.com. Only the owner of each tab can control the image.  New images will be released by the artist and pushed directly to IPFS, which will sync with the corresponding ERC-721 token. HODLERS will have the option to *clear cookies* which will choose a variation at random. Once every variation has been released, HODLERS will be able to choose which image they would like to have displayed from the available variations of said token.

meta.name: Indolência
meta.description:
Indolência. Como escrito por John Keats :”Foram-se as três e eu só queria asas ainda;
Loucura! O que é o Amor? Quem sabe onde ele mora?” Amor é um tema universal, e, desta vez, dois artistas convergem juntos para explorar o conteúdo de ambas visões. Um com um amor que explode, o outro com um amor frio e lento. Ambos os estilos confluem-se para uma visão única do que é e pode ser amar.

Indolence. As written by John Keats: “They faded, and, forsooth! I wanted wings:
O folly! What is Love? and where is it?” Love is a universal theme, and this time two artists converge together to explore this content with both visions. One has a love that explodes. The other one, a love that is cold and slow. Both styles come together to form a unique vision of what is and what can be LOVE. 

The sales of this 1/1 piece will be split between cechk and ih0dl equally. 

A royalty (14%) percentage of each sale after the original will also be split equally.  7% for each artist

meta.description:
I wanted my first work as a verified artist on Rarible to be special. I’ve been holding onto this for a while now. 

To me, crypto is a space of open creativity, we should embrace this technology and ideology. 

We have enough “influencers” in the crypto space to shill links until the end of time. 

We need more advocates that are willing to educate and be a node of open-sourced knowledge for their peers,  just like our platform.

Advocation is a dedication to decentralization.  

Take the red pill.

This elf was born as a collaboration with the Elven Punks, check them out on opensea here:
https://opensea.io/collection/elvenpunks
They are also on twitter @elvenpunks
TrashPunks are in no was affiliated with larva labs or crypto punks. Trash punks are an artist parody made with much respect for the original creators for paving the way for the world of NFTs. 


Each Trash Punk will be manually trashed using digital techniques - most likely procreate - to make these little bastards the trashiest punks in town.
